Antwerp 21 feb 1682
m. my last to you was onthe 18 curtt to which referve you, since
have been with John button, butt no mathers to be hadd att huyl
onelj 2 bales of which the owner lives in the countrey, & I
hath promised to gest them for you, & that he will payfor the
of which I sale know the succes before next post. there is 2
bales more here in towne out of the carty of hulst, butt
the owner was in zealand, yett & lendeavour toh ave them
as best Jean: there is 6 balese more out of the land of
tergoes, which sort is most estimed and as oI B lells of mee
they take 300 ee mullen out of 1000: onberoofde, when
those of hulft take butt 15 oce, I made hm come hethes
to seethose goods & hetold mee that he never sauany as
good, butt the factors nad no orders to self att any rate, yett
ourfortune is, that one of the owners is come up from
tergoes with the makett day & 4 bought 2 bales of hin
of about 1100: ap. att ƒ 38:10 &. cont 2 p c 4 p cet for
the mary. that is tobe payd in hollands morry & 16 cet. for
ready morry I But sayes that they 6e better bij 6 a 1 pecr.
them them from hulst, & that if wee had the other 4 o
the same sort they would set oft a worst parcell so I'll endeavour
to do for you what I can, for I shall content my self with a provision andly
the 2 bales I made mention off att ƒ32- are sence contramanded to sell, so there is
butt 8 bales in all in factors handes yett so sell, except what is by the dyers & which
want itt for their owne provisions, if I can gett any more of the others Ill do my best
endeavonr, wee pay no duties outward, so please to advise mee if I shall dispatch then
bij way of Brugges or holland. I have wrott to Rotterdam & advise that mathers o
beroofde sell for ƒ 34„35 & ƒ36-, so have you given orders there, you might have been
well served, by all apearence they must aise, yett if itt not falls out as with, the come
& other graines, which beeng risen att first are a falling now, whoever you are more
used to that trade, & know best how itt is att present with you, hitt I am sure there are
yett good quantites in holland, you have nott mited what quantiie I might buy for

Landen mr. Ednund Warner
mij last do you was on the 18th curtt. sence non from you, the packett n°. 17 werst forward yasterdoy
& so shall follow the rest consceutively, I shall hardeley be able to provide for £300 se more att
chose rates for I have had goods brought in to day & the warck women dare afke more
yett upen faire promises to give more, wl the occasion & markett doth command
have lest their goods att the best prijse, so I hope to procure yett some assortm
before they ise, having bough yosterday & this day for about 4 a 500 gud. intended
for you, Intan have this day drawne on you £120 payable att 1½ vr
to the order of m. Jac Bonwens valew of him self, & £160- payable to the ord. of mr. Henry
Maynard valew of Cornelie vander wiel, boutt att 35.2 the latter att 2 ts, which please
to accept & pass to acctt accordingly & in alle occasions command mee
Londen m Henry Maynard
mij last to you was on the 18t cur. to which please to be referred because sence non from
you, so the cheifley for covert to the inclosed bill for £160 on m. Edmund Warner att 2
ƒt0 att 35:2 for which please to procure the needfull & past to yd acctt itt is noted for
the valeu of Cornelis van de wid proforma I'll do all I can to remitt now every wee
something to cleare of my old dobt. if you finde ex. would ane & todraw to some
advantidge, you might dispose of £150- a £200 for my accctt. att one or 2 uso eather
